<font color="#FF0000">ENOUGH IS ENOUGH!!!</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jul 27 16:17:25 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br>
     I just got back on line after 3 weeks.  How dare you accuse me of posting Communist propaganda?  When I said that it was known in our intelligence company that Ho would win an election; I meant just that.  The data came from our counter intelligence section's sources in Binh Dinh Province, and had been corroborated over a period of months.  None of this came from NVA sources.  Just because this doesn't agree with your worldview, doesn't mean it wasn't so.  Despite the depredations of the VC and NVA, Ho was fondly remembered by many for his fight against the French.<br>
     How would you have liked it if I had cast aspersions on your combat remembrances because my experiences were different?  I thought a Marine was supposed to have more honor than that.  Disagree with my views all you like, but if you're going to call into question items from my Vietnam experience, you better be able to cite the military reports, chapter and verse.<br>
     Also, would appreciate it if you would quit selectively  quoting history.  Traditionally, Vietnam divided into North , Center (roughly Quang Tri to Bao Lac) and South, with the emperor at Hue in the Center.  The division of the country in 1954 took place largely because no way in hell would the US allow a Communist (Ho) to take power in the entire country, even by a free election.  That does not mean there were not Vietnamese, especially the thousands of Catholic refugees from the North, that would rather give allegiance to a non-Communist South Vietnam than a united Vietnam under the Communists.  Still, there's a just as good a case for considering Vietnam one country, even when it was divided as Germany or Ireland.  I think you'll find that in all the captured NVA documents, the North Vietnamese considered the South to be part of the same country, and that's acknowledging that they discriminated against the Southerners who went into the VC both before and after the war.<br>
     Not that you should have done different, but most of the NVA you killed were probably not Communist party members, but peasants drafted for cannon fodder.<br>
     There is nothing wrong with being proud of having served.  In the face of ambiguous information, you go with your own country.  But if you feel that it's necessary that participation in the Vietnam War must be viewed as taking part in a 100% right grand cause, you're going to be spending the rest of your life either fighting or ignoring the considerable evidence that the enterprise was flawed in many, many ways.  Now, I did NOT say the US's motives were out and out wrong and evil; and usually only hindsight is 20-20.  But as the saying goes: &quot;By it's fruit you shall know it&quot;.  A lot of the fruit of the Vietnam War is rotten.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


